==English==

===Etymology===
* First attested in the 1570's.
* From {{etyl|fro}} {{term|accoster|lang=for}}, from {{etyl|VL.}} {{term|accosto|accosto|to come alongside someone|lang=la}}, from {{term|ad||near|lang-la}} + {{term|costa||rib, side|lang=la}}

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ə.ˈkɔst/|/ə.ˈkɑst/}}
* {{audio|en-us-accost.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{transitive}} To approach and speak to boldly or aggressively, as with a demand or request.
#*{{quote-news
    | date = 21 August 2012
    | first = Ed
    | last = Pilkington
    | title = Death penalty on trial: should Reggie Clemons live or die?
    | newspaper = The Guardian
    | url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2012/aug/21/death-penalty-trial-reggie-clemons?newsfeed=true
    | page = 
    | passage = The Missouri prosecutors' case against Clemons, based partly on incriminating testimony given by his co-defendants, was that Clemons was part of a group of four youths who '''accosted''' the sisters on the Chain of Rocks Bridge one dark night in April 1991. 
}}
# {{context|transitive|obsolete}} To join side to side; to border; hence, to sail along the coast or side of.
#* So much [of Lapland] as '''accosts''' the sea. - Fuller
# {{context|transitive|obsolete}} To approach; to come up to.
# {{transitive}} To speak to first; to address; to greet.
#* Him, Satan thus '''accosts''' - Milton
#* '''1847''', {{w|Charlotte Brontë}}, {{w|Jane Eyre}}, Chapter XVIII
#*: She approached the basin, and bent over it as if to fill her pitcher; she again lifted it to her head. The personage on the well-brink now seemed to '''accost''' her; to make some request—"She hasted, let down her pitcher on her hand, and gave him to drink."
# {{context|intransitive|obsolete}} To adjoin; to lie alongside.
#* The shores which to the sea '''accost''' - Spenser
# To [[solicit]] sexually.

